Finally, we can now equal the expressions for the bonds' value to obtain an equation in which the only unknown variable is *t* (if we assign an arbitrary value to *F*, e.g. $1000).

We can solve the resulting equation for *t* using a financial calculator or a spreadsheet:
$$
\begin{align*}
\dfrac{C}{\text{Current yield}}\cdot 100 &= \dfrac{C}{YTM}\left( 1 - \dfrac{1}{(1+YTM)^t} \right) + \dfrac{F}{(1+YTM)^t}\\[2.5em]
\dfrac{\$1,000 \cdot 0.08}{\text{0.0755}}\cdot 100 &= \dfrac{\$1,000 \cdot 0.08}{0.072}\left( 1 - \dfrac{1}{(1+0.072)^t} \right) + \dfrac{\$1,000}{(1+0.072)^t}\\[2.5em]
\implies t &= \boxed{11.06}
\end{align*}
$$
Therefore, we can conclude that the time to maturity of the bonds is **11.06 years**.

Let's inset what we have in the previous formula.

$$\begin{aligned}
\$1,059.60&=\$80\times\dfrac{1-\left(1+7.2\%\right)^\text
{-n}}{7.2\%}+\dfrac{\$1,000}{\left(1+7.2\%\right)^\text{n
}}\\[15pt]
\$1,059.60&=\$80\times\dfrac{1-\left(1.072\right)^\text{-n}}{0.072}+\dfrac{\$1,000}{\left(1.072\right)^\text{n}}
\end{aligned}$$

If we use Spreadsheets, we will get n=11.05 years. Because the years can not be a decimal number, we have to round the result to a higher number. **The bond has 12 years more left**.
